<section xml:id="absolutevalues">
  <title>Absolute Values</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x\in \mathbb{R}</m>,
        we define the <term>absolute value</term>
        or <term>modulus</term> of <m>x</m> to be
        <me>
          |x| = \left\{\begin{array}{ll} x \amp  \mbox{ if }  x\geq 0 \\ -x \amp  \mbox{ if }  x\leq 0 \end{array} \right.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    Geometrically,
    <m>|x|</m> measures the distance from <m>x</m> to <m>0</m> along the real line, e.g.
    <m>|-3|=3</m>.
  </p>
  <lemma>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m>,
        <me>
          -|x|\leq x\leq |x|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>
  <proof>
    <p>
      If <m>x\geq 0</m>, then since <m>|x|\geq 0</m>,
      <me>
        -|x|\leq 0\leq x=|x|
      </me>
      and if <m>x\leq 0</m>, then <m>-x=|x|</m>, so <m>x=-|x|</m>, hence
      <me>
        -|x|=x\leq 0\leq |x|
      </me>.
    </p>
  </proof>
  <note>
    <title>Proofs with $|\cdot|$</title>
    <p>
      Since the definition of <m>|x|</m> is defined in terms of cases,
      a proof involving absolute values may need to be split into cases depending on what sign <m>x</m> has.
    </p>
  </note>
  <example xml:id="ex__x__2_x_2">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x\in \mathbb{R}</m>, <m>|x|^2=x^2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We split the proof into two cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Case 1:</em> If <m>x\geq 0</m>.
        Then <m>|x|=x</m> and so <m>|x|^2=x^2</m>,
        which proves the claim in this case.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Case 2:</em> If <m>x\lt 0</m>,
        then <m>|x|=-x</m>, so <m>|x|^2=(-x)^2=(-1)^2x^2=1</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus, the claim is true in all cases.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For which <m>x\in\mathbb{R}</m> do we have <m>|x-1|\lt |x+2|</m>?
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that the signs of the absolute value change as <m>x</m> crosses <m>1</m> and <m>-2</m>,
        so we split into cases depending on where <m>x</m> lies in relation to these numbers:
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Case 1:</em> If <m>x\leq -2</m>, then <m>x-1\lt 0</m>,
        so <m>|x-1|=1-x</m> and <m>x+2\leq 0</m> so <m>|x+2|=-2-x</m>,
        so <m>|x-1|\lt |x+2|</m> holds if and only if <m>1-x\lt -2-x</m>,
        or equivalently, <m>2\lt -1</m>, which never holds.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Case 2:</em> If <m>-2\leq x\leq 1</m>,
        then <m>|x-1|=1-x</m> again but <m>|x+2|=x+2</m>,
        so <m>|x-1|\lt |x+2|</m> if and only if
        <m>1-x\lt x+2</m> , i.e. if <m>-1\lt 2x</m>,
        so the only <m>x</m>'s between <m>-2</m> and <m>1</m> where the inequality holds is for <m>x>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Case 3:</em> If <m>x\geq 1</m>,
        then <m>|x-1|=x-1</m> and <m>|x+2|=x+2</m>,
        so <m>|x-1|\lt |x+2|</m> if and only if <m>x-1\lt x+2</m>,
        i.e. if <m>-1\lt 2</m>, which always holds.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bringing it all together,
        we see that our inequality holds if and only if <m>-\frac{1}{2}\lt x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <lemma xml:id="l__xy___x__y_">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x,y\in \mathbb{R}</m>, <m>|xy|=|x|\cdot |y|</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>
  <p>
    We leave the proof as an exercise.
  </p>
  <theorem>
    <title>The Triangle Inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x,y\in\mathbb{R}</m>,
        <me>
          |x+y|\leq |x|+|y|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <proof>
    <p>
      We split into cases,
      and will use the fact that <m>\pm x\leq |x|</m> by definition.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Case 1:</em> If <m>x+y\geq 0</m>, then
      <me>
        |x+y|=x+y\leq |x|+|y|
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Case 2:</em> If <m>x+y\leq 0</m>, then
      <me>
        |x+y|=-(x+y)=-x+(-y)\leq |x|+|y|
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus, the claim is true in all cases.
    </p>
  </proof>
  <p>
    We leave the following corollary as an exercise.
  </p>
  <corollary>
    <title>The Reverse Triangle Inequality</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For <m>x,y\in\mathbb{R}</m>,
        <me>
          \bigl||x|-|y|\bigr|\leq |x+y|
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In particular,
        <me>
          |x|-|y|\leq |x+y|
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </corollary>
</section>